# Skillfold - Multi-Agent AI Pipeline Configuration

You are working on a project that uses Skillfold to configure multi-agent AI pipelines.
Skillfold compiles YAML config into agent skill files for various AI coding tools.

## Config File Structure

The config file is `skillfold.yaml` with four top-level sections:

```yaml
resources:   # Resource namespace declarations for state locations
skills:      # Atomic and composed skill definitions
state:       # Typed state schema for inter-agent data flow
team:        # Orchestrator and execution flow graph
```

Optional top-level fields: `name`, `imports`.

## Skills Section

Skills are split into `atomic` and `composed`:

```yaml
skills:
  atomic:
    # Local skill (directory containing SKILL.md)
    my-skill: ./skills/my-skill
    # Remote skill (GitHub URL)
    remote-skill: https://github.com/org/repo/tree/main/skills/name
    # npm skill
    lib-skill: npm:package-name/skills/name

  composed:
    my-agent:
      compose: [skill-a, skill-b, skill-c]
      description: "What this agent does."
```

Key rules:
- Atomic skills point to directories containing a SKILL.md file
- Composed skills list atomic skills in `compose` order (bodies are concatenated)
- Composition is recursive - a composed skill can reference other composed skills
- Every skill name referenced in `compose` must exist in `atomic` or `composed`
- Descriptions should be concise, action-oriented sentences

## State Section

State defines typed data that flows between agents:

```yaml
state:
  # Custom type definition (capitalized name)
  Review:
    approved: bool
    feedback: string

  # State variable (lowercase name)
  plan:
    type: string

  tasks:
    type: list<Task>

  review:
    type: Review
    location:
      github-issues: { repo: org/repo, label: review }
```

Type rules:
- Primitive types: `string`, `bool`
- Custom types: defined inline with capitalized names
- List types: `list<TypeName>`
- Locations are optional and map state to external services
- Built-in integrations: `github-issues`, `github-discussions`, `github-pull-requests`

## Team Section

Defines the execution flow graph:

```yaml
team:
  orchestrator: orchestrator-agent  # optional, appends generated plan

  flow:
    - planner:
        writes: [state.plan]
      then: engineer

    - engineer:
        reads: [state.plan]
        writes: [state.implementation]
      then: reviewer

    - reviewer:
        reads: [state.implementation]
        writes: [state.review]
      then:
        - when: review.approved == true
          to: end
        - when: review.approved == false
          to: engineer
```

Flow rules:
- Each node names a composed skill and declares `reads`/`writes` on state
- `then` can be a single target, `end`, or conditional routing with `when`/`to`
- State paths use `state.` prefix in reads/writes, drop prefix in when-clauses
- Conditional routes must cover all possible outcomes
- The graph must be acyclic (except for explicit loops with exit conditions)
- Map nodes support parallel execution over list state

## Resources Section

Declares resource namespaces for state location validation:

```yaml
resources:
  github:
    url: https://github.com/{repo}
```

## Imports

Pull in skills, state, and resources from other configs:

```yaml
imports:
  - npm:skillfold/library/skillfold.yaml
  - ./other-config/skillfold.yaml
```

Imports merge `skills`, `state`, and `resources`. The `team` section is always local.

## CLI Commands

Core commands (run from project root):

```bash
# Compile pipeline (default output to build/)
npx skillfold

# Compile for a specific target
npx skillfold --target claude-code    # .claude/agents/ and .claude/skills/
npx skillfold --target cursor         # .cursor/rules/
npx skillfold --target codex           # AGENTS.md
npx skillfold --target copilot         # .github/copilot-instructions.md
npx skillfold --target windsurf        # .windsurf/rules/
npx skillfold --target gemini          # .gemini/agents/ and .gemini/skills/

# Validate config without compiling
npx skillfold validate

# Check compiled output is up-to-date (for CI)
npx skillfold --check

# Watch for changes and auto-recompile
npx skillfold watch

# List pipeline skills, state, and flow
npx skillfold list

# Generate interactive flow graph
npx skillfold graph --html > pipeline.html

# Run the pipeline
npx skillfold run --target claude-code
npx skillfold run --target claude-code --resume   # resume from checkpoint
npx skillfold run --target claude-code --dry-run   # preview without executing

# Search for shared skills on npm
npx skillfold search [query]

# Initialize a new pipeline project
npx skillfold init
npx skillfold init --template dev-team

# Package as a Claude Code plugin
npx skillfold plugin
```

## Common Patterns

### Linear Pipeline
```yaml
flow:
  - agent-a:
      writes: [state.output-a]
    then: agent-b
  - agent-b:
      reads: [state.output-a]
      writes: [state.output-b]
    then: end
```

### Review Loop
```yaml
flow:
  - writer:
      writes: [state.draft]
    then: reviewer
  - reviewer:
      reads: [state.draft]
      writes: [state.review]
    then:
      - when: review.approved == true
        to: end
      - when: review.approved == false
        to: writer
```

### Parallel Map
```yaml
flow:
  - processor:
      reads: [state.items]
      writes: [state.results]
      map:
        over: state.items
        as: item
        flow:
          - handler:
              reads: [item]
              writes: [item.result]
            then: end
    then: end
```

## Best Practices

- Keep atomic skills small and focused on a single capability
- Use descriptive skill names that indicate what the skill does
- Declare reads/writes accurately - the compiler validates state access
- Use `npx skillfold validate` before committing config changes
- Use `npx skillfold --check` in CI to verify compiled output stays current
- Use the library skills (`npm:skillfold/library/skillfold.yaml`) as building blocks
- Prefer `npm:` imports for shared skills over direct file paths
- Run `npx skillfold graph --html > pipeline.html` to visualize complex flows
- Use `skillfold.local.yaml` for local overrides (gitignored by default)
